@node Overview
@chapter Overview

@samp{window-extras.el} extends Emacs' built-in @code{window.el} with commands for switching between windows, moving buffers across windows, and intelligently splitting frames. Emacs' default window management commands are powerful but sometimes cumbersome for common workflows like toggling between two windows or moving a buffer to an adjacent window without losing context.

The main capabilities are:

@itemize
@item
@strong{Switching to the last window.} A quick toggle between the current and most recently used window, including the minibuffer (@ref{Switching to the last window}).
@item
@strong{Intelligent splitting.} Automatically splitting frames into two or three windows based on frame width (@ref{Splitting}).
@item
@strong{Buffer movement.} Moving the current buffer to an adjacent window or swapping buffers between windows (@ref{Buffer movement}).
@item
@strong{Minibuffer and side window access.} Jumping to the active minibuffer or selecting the leftmost/rightmost window (@ref{Special window access}).
@end itemize

@node User options
@chapter User options

@menu
* @code{window-extras-frame-split-width-threshold}::
@end menu

@node @code{window-extras-frame-split-width-threshold}
@section @code{window-extras-frame-split-width-threshold}

@vindex window-extras-frame-split-width-threshold
The user option @code{window-extras-frame-split-width-threshold} specifies the minimum frame width (in columns) at which @code{window-extras-split-if-unsplit} (@ref{Splitting}) will create a three-window layout instead of a two-window layout. On wide displays, three side-by-side windows can be more productive than two very wide ones.

The default value is @code{350}. The type is an integer. You might lower this value if you use a smaller font or increase it for larger fonts.

